title: Brisbane Ranges - Moths
description: The Brisbane Ranges has a biodiverse moth fauna.  Many detected species have yet to be identified.  This collection is an attempt to offer identification features, in photos and tags, that may assist others observing moths in the Brisbane Ranges to apply correct species identification to their observations.

items.title: Anthela repleta
items.content_text: In photo 2, the moth has laid eggs on the stem of Pultenaea gunnii subsp. tuberculata.

items.title: Anestia ombrophanes
items.content_text: This is a lighter colour form - can be variable.

items.title: Metrocampa biplaga
items.content_text: This moth has been reclassified to (Azelina) biplaga

items.title: Arhodia lasiocamparia
items.content_text: Top photo is the female, lower photo is the male.

items.title: Opsirhina lechriodes
items.content_text: Both are same species: one injured with no wing spot on left side and no 'snout'.

items.title: Sinpunctiptilia emissalis
items.content_text: Also known as Platyptilia emissalis. Feeds on Digger's Speedwell (Derwentia perfoliata).

items.title: Alucita phricodes
items.content_text: Unmistakable - has both fore and hindwings wings deeply cleft into numerous narrow lobes.  This one was about 1.8cm from wing tip to wing tip.

items.title: Phrataria transcissata
items.content_text: This moth is particularly difficult to photograph because it rarely sits with its wings open.
